799
01:13:32,375 --> 01:13:38,899
[SPEAKER_06]: We're going to start out with a tune poem called Hard by the Mystic.

800
01:13:44,212 --> 01:13:50,036
[SPEAKER_06]: They gave my people the lowlands, and not much of it, just a few streets hard by the river.

801
01:13:51,077 --> 01:13:54,960
[SPEAKER_06]: Banks turned a blind eye behind the red lines, and it wasn't about the money.

802
01:13:56,081 --> 01:13:58,042
[SPEAKER_06]: Class was an irresistible force.

803
01:13:58,822 --> 01:14:00,504
[SPEAKER_06]: Race was a movable object.

804
01:14:01,636 --> 01:14:17,277
[SPEAKER_06]: Perhaps it wasn't a written rule, but white folks knew the legal to to keep us in our place in this mystic valley space where slaves and rum and ships had built some mansions, made some millionaires, and hid some old money.

805
01:14:18,379 --> 01:14:20,320
[SPEAKER_06]: So it was hard by the mystic we went.

806
01:14:21,001 --> 01:14:22,782
[SPEAKER_06]: Muddy and a bit turned down.

807
01:14:23,302 --> 01:14:27,685
[SPEAKER_06]: The only place where one could be brown in this ancient Middlesex County town.

808
01:14:28,505 --> 01:14:29,566
[SPEAKER_06]: But we named it.

809
01:14:30,186 --> 01:14:31,047
[SPEAKER_06]: We claimed it.

810
01:14:31,587 --> 01:14:32,948
[SPEAKER_06]: We made it our own.

811
01:14:34,729 --> 01:14:42,353
[SPEAKER_06]: Even in the heat of summer when the shores were parched and the soil was rank with the decay of aquatic alchemy, we were one with the river.

812
01:14:43,094 --> 01:14:46,096
[SPEAKER_06]: We followed its flow to the lakes and the sandy beach front.

813
01:14:47,216 --> 01:14:52,299
[SPEAKER_06]: On our own Jordan shore, we baptized and blessed our brothers and sisters in Christ.

814
01:14:52,600 --> 01:15:01,785
[SPEAKER_06]: We caught the little fishes to go with our loaves of bread and became the teeming multitude who our Lord Jesus fed, hired by the mystic.

815
01:15:05,027 --> 01:15:06,308
[SPEAKER_06]: We became community.

816
01:15:06,969 --> 01:15:08,369
[SPEAKER_06]: We commanded unity.

817
01:15:09,150 --> 01:15:13,513
[SPEAKER_06]: We embraced the village and raised up our children in the way they should go.

818
01:15:28,181 --> 01:15:33,283
[SPEAKER_06]: As the river ebbs and flows, the tides will turn and our fortune grows.

819
01:15:33,863 --> 01:15:35,723
[SPEAKER_06]: A few more streets become our home.

820
01:15:36,283 --> 01:15:39,044
[SPEAKER_06]: Houses on Sharon join Kin on Jerome.

821
01:15:39,864 --> 01:15:45,246
[SPEAKER_06]: From Duggar Park to the railroad tracks, the white folks make more room for blacks.

822
01:15:45,786 --> 01:15:47,707
[SPEAKER_06]: The color line recedes a bit.

823
01:15:48,207 --> 01:15:50,688
[SPEAKER_06]: Church and school and center fit.

824
01:15:50,988 --> 01:15:55,109
[SPEAKER_06]: The ville becomes the heart of it, hard by the mystic shore.

825
01:16:06,095 --> 01:16:12,739
[SPEAKER_06]: Now the worm has surely turned, and folks who left have surely learned things couldn't stay the same.

826
01:16:13,739 --> 01:16:16,300
[SPEAKER_06]: That muddy mystic most days is clean.

827
01:16:16,861 --> 01:16:19,002
[SPEAKER_06]: The banks are freshly cut and green.

828
01:16:19,722 --> 01:16:24,505
[SPEAKER_06]: Faces once distinctly brown are not the only ones in town.

829
01:16:26,158 --> 01:16:41,033
[SPEAKER_06]: These streets that once were our confines must now embrace what gentry defines, condominium culture, bedroom convenience, university sprawl, access, egress, invest, and dispossess.

830
01:16:49,358 --> 01:16:52,763
[SPEAKER_06]: Now those lowlands have become the highlights of a trending city.

831
01:16:53,384 --> 01:17:00,094
[SPEAKER_06]: And sometimes success isn't pretty when it's at the expense of your black and brown and tan friends.

832
01:17:06,326 --> 01:17:12,489
[SPEAKER_06]: And yet, the river still turns and bends from where it begins to where it ends.

833
01:17:13,830 --> 01:17:26,336
[SPEAKER_06]: The only place where one could be brown in this ancient Middlesex County town, where we named it and claimed it and made it our own.

834
01:17:30,999 --> 01:17:31,479
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

835
01:17:32,439 --> 01:17:33,300
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you very much.

836
01:17:35,239 --> 01:18:00,457
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, so that's the beginning of the story, but the story continues, and it continues as the neighborhood has evolved, and the evolution is stark and pretty dramatic, and we have kind of quantified it with a piece called Gentrified.

837
01:18:20,104 --> 01:18:23,728
[SPEAKER_06]: They talk about renovating, reimagining, and rehabilitating.

838
01:18:24,389 --> 01:18:28,234
[SPEAKER_06]: They rave about new visions, new horizons, and new perspectives.

839
